          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "All three changes are in and building cleanly. Here's a summary of what was done and why:\n\n---\n\n**Why some entries had no `prompt_id`**\n\nThis was a timing/race condition. When Cursor fires `postToolUse` for the first tool in a response, its SQLite DB may not yet have persisted the user message that triggered the whole response. So the `prompt_id` scan at checkpoint creation time finds nothing. By the time the *last* tool in the batch fires, the DB has caught up — which is why only the final checkpoint (index 4 in your log) had a `prompt_id`.\n\nThe existing backfill in `update_prompts_to_latest` only patched the *last* checkpoint per conversation. The fix in `post_commit.rs` now uses the full (post-race) transcript to backfill ALL checkpoints in the conversation by timestamp: for each checkpoint that still lacks a `prompt_id`, it finds the last user message whose timestamp is ≤ the checkpoint's Unix timestamp and assigns that message's bubble ID.\n\n**`author_id` → `conversation_id`**\n\nRenamed the field in `ChangeHistoryEntry`. The value is the short hash of `(tool, conversation_uuid)` — it's a conversation identifier, not an author. The old name was misleading because there are already `author_id` fields all over the attribution/attestation structs that mean something different (the attribution owner). Changed in the struct, the builder closure, and the plan doc.\n\n**`agent_type` field**\n\nAdded `agent_type: Option<String>` to `ChangeHistoryEntry`, populated from `agent_id.tool` (e.g. `\"cursor\"`). Human checkpoints emit `null` for this field (same as `conversation_id` and `model`), so it's skipped in serialization via `skip_serializing_if`.\n\nThe updated output will look like:\n```json\n{\n  \"timestamp\": 1774583003,\n  \"kind\": \"ai_agent\",\n  \"conversation_id\": \"6b9e********93b0\",\n  \"agent_type\": \"cursor\",\n  \"prompt_id\": \"607eee96-d248-48b3-a180-7f6777b1077a\",\n  \"model\": \"claude-4.6-sonnet-medium-thinking\",\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nHuman entries remain compact with just `timestamp`, `kind`, `files`, and `line_stats`.",
